  <text>
    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Clifton Friday Evg.</p>
      <p>Is not the enclosed a nice letter? What a contrast to E.N's reply, (altho' to the very same words from me, since E. N forwarded the unlucky P.S to its rightful owner)! The modesty of Mrs Joanna, whose own reputation would give her a right to treat me as a literary nobody, is ridiculously diverse from the arrogant &amp; condescending tone of his reply.</p>
      <p>I think that (tho' I would rather drop the disagreeable correspondence) there are some reasons why I ought to reply,</p>
      <p>but briefly &amp; in a few very explicit lines. You are not aware of his violent previous bitterness &amp; intemperate vituperations against both you &amp; me; &amp; I consider that I should not now leave things between us on an indefinite footing; just that he may have the satisfaction of turning his back on me the first time we may accidentally meet.</p>
      <p>I think that I ought to settle on what footing we are to be, &amp; also the true ground of my alienation from &amp; contempt for him, viz (his ungrateful &amp; ungentlemanlike tone of mind).</p>
      <p>The Hen admired my yesterday's letter to Kraemer very much.</p>
      <p>I hope you may equally have</p>
      <p>liked it.</p>
      <p>Surely the Crosses must be a resource to you in the evenings.</p>
      <p>The Hen is a poor wretched creature still, &amp; much in status quo.</p>
    </div></body>
